		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Dei, et Regis vasallus: Artis, et Virtutis secretarius: Entelechia[e].
						Monopragmaticus: Euschemosynes, et ironia[e]
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="90" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						arcanus politicus: vir ex tetragono absolutus.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The vasal of God and King, the secretary of Art and Virtue, is Actualization.
				Having skill in one thing: an arcane politician of Refinement and Irony; a man freed from the square.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="FR">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						 ( Combats Olympiques, non pour or,)
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="90" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						ny argent, ains pour la seule vertu. Concupiscenses,
						Les Pygmees. )
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Olympic Combat: for neither gold nor silver, but for the single virtue. Pygmies, concupiscences. <!-- CG: I really have no idea what the last part is. Possible connection with, which mentions Olympic Combat, Pygmies, and Concupiscences: https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BxKZ_L0zJFYC&pg=PA935&lpg=PA935&dq=Concupiscences+Les+Pygmees&source=bl&ots=a2PchYYYWW&sig=gxRyeBheciSnk2yCjxAUlBpmBf4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CD0Q6AEwBGoVChMIkqC714ihxwIVSkkaCh2MswFV#v=onepage&q=Concupiscences%20Les%20Pygmees&f=false-->
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="270" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Matutinus ante gallum: meridianus super Solem: vespertinus, qualis
						Sol oriens apud Antipodes. Omnes tardi gradi, aut retrogradi,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="270" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						pra[e]ter vnum Gra[e]cum; vnumq[ue] Romanum;
						et paucissimos euisdem ala[e]. 
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Early morning, before the rooster; at noon, above the sun; by evening, like
				the sun rising on the other side of the world. All are slow to move forward or
				backward, except one Greek and one Roman, and very few of the same wing.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		
